Linear search and binary search are both algorithms used to search for a specific value in a given data set. However, they differ in their efficiency and the type of data sets they work best with.

A linear search algorithm searches for a given value in a data set by traversing the data set from the beginning to the end, checking each element until the desired value is found or the end of the data set is reached. This algorithm is simple to implement and works well for small data sets, but becomes inefficient for larger data sets.

Here's an example of a linear search algorithm in C:
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int linearSearch(int arr[], int n, int x) {
    int i;
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (arr[i] == x) {
            return i;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

int main() {
    int arr[] = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9};
    int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);
    int x = 7;
    int result = linearSearch(arr, n, x);
    if (result == -1) {
        printf("Element not found");
    } else {
        printf("Element found at index %d", result);
    }
    return 0;
}
```
