Yes, we can add the `ApplicativeFunctor` interface to the `PromiseMonad` object to allow it to perform validation. The `ApplicativeFunctor` interface requires the addition of an `ap` method to the monad object, which will apply a function wrapped in a monad to a value wrapped in a monad.

Here's an updated implementation of the `PromiseMonad` object that includes the `ApplicativeFunctor` interface:
```javascript
const PromiseMonad = {
  unit: (value) => Promise.resolve(value),
  flatMap: (promise, f) => promise.then(f),
  fail: (error) => Promise.reject(error),
  ap: (monad1, monad2) => monad1.flatMap((f) => monad2.flatMap((x) => PromiseMonad.unit(f(x)))),
};
```
With the `ap` method, we can now use the `PromiseMonad` object to perform validation. Here's an example of how we can use this updated `PromiseMonad` object to validate an email address:
```javascript
// Define the PromiseMonad object with MonadFail and ApplicativeFunctor interfaces
const PromiseMonad = {
  unit: (value) => Promise.resolve(value),
  flatMap: (promise, f) => promise.then(f),
  fail: (error) => Promise.reject(error),
  ap: (monad1, monad2) =>
    monad1.flatMap((f) => monad2.flatMap((x) => PromiseMonad.unit(f(x)))),
};

// Define a function that validates an email address and returns a Promise
const validateEmail = (email) =>
  PromiseMonad.unit((email) =>
    email.match(/^\w+@[a-zA-Z_]+?\.[a-zA-Z]{2,3}$/) ? email : PromiseMonad.fail('Invalid email')
  ).ap(PromiseMonad.unit(email));

// Use the ap method to apply the validateEmail function to a value wrapped in a monad
validateEmail('test@example.com')
  .then((result) => console.log(result)) // Logs "test@example.com"
  .catch((error) => console.error(error));

validateEmail('invalid-email')
  .then((result) => console.log(result))
  .catch((error) => console.error(error)); // Logs "Invalid email"
