```
import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;

public class NoOrderOfOperations {

    public static int evaluate(String expr) {
        int result = 0;
        int current = 0;
        char operator = '+';

        for (int i = 0; i < expr.length(); i++) {
            char c = expr.charAt(i);
            if (Character.isDigit(c)) {
                current = current * 10 + (c - '0');
            } else {
                result = applyOperator(result, operator, current);
                operator = c;
                current = 0;
            }
        }
        result = applyOperator(result, operator, current);
        return result;
    }

    private static int applyOperator(int result, char operator, int current) {
        switch (operator) {
            case '+':
                return result + current;
            case '-':
                return result - current;
            case '*':
                return result * current;
        }
        // return the same value if no operator is applied
        return result;
    }

    @Test
    public void testEvaluate() {
        assertEquals(56, evaluate("3+5*7"));
        assertEquals(-36, evaluate("4-8*9*1"));
        assertEquals(0, evaluate("0"));
        assertEquals(362880, evaluate("1*2*3*4*5*6*7*8*9"));
    }
}
```
This refactored program uses JUnit test cases to check the results of the `evaluate` method. The `assertEquals` method is used to check that the returned value of the `evaluate` method is equal to the expected value. JUnit is a framework that makes it easy to write repeatable and automated tests for Java code. This approach makes testing more efficient, as it allows the developer to check all the test cases with a single command.

