Without using the "robotjs" module, you can still take a screenshot of an entire email message, including the area cut off from scrolling, on the desktop Outlook app on Windows using Node.js. Here's an example code snippet using the "puppeteer" and "sharp" modules:
```javascript
const puppeteer = require('puppeteer');
const sharp = require('sharp');

(async () => {
  const browser = await puppeteer.launch();
  const page = await browser.newPage();

  // Set the URL of the email message you want to capture
  const url = 'https://outlook.com/your-email-url';

  await page.goto(url, { waitUntil: 'networkidle0' });

  // Wait for the email to fully load
  await page.waitForTimeout(5000);

  // Scroll to the bottom of the email
  await page.evaluate(() => {
    window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight);
  });

  // Get the position and size of the email message area
  const messageArea = await page.$eval('#message-area-selector', (el) => {
    const { x, y, width, height } = el.getBoundingClientRect();
    return { x, y, width, height };
  });

  // Take a screenshot of the message area
  const screenshot = await page.screenshot({
    clip: {
      x: messageArea.x,
      y: messageArea.y,
      width: messageArea.width,
      height: messageArea.height,
    },
    fullPage: true,
  });

  // Save the screenshot as a PNG file
  await sharp(screenshot).png().toFile('email-screenshot.png');

  await browser.close();

  console.log('Screenshot saved as email-screenshot.png');
})();
```
In this code snippet, we use the "puppeteer" module to automate the Chrome browser and take a screenshot of the email message area.

We first launch a new Chrome browser and navigate to the URL of the email message you want to capture. We wait for the email to fully load using the "waitForTimeout()" method.

We then use the "evaluate()" method to scroll to the bottom of the email and get the position and size of the email message area using the selector "#message-area-selector". You can replace this selector with the appropriate selector for your email client.

We use the "screenshot()" method to take a screenshot of the message area and set the "fullPage" option to "true" to capture the entire email message, including the area cut off from scrolling.

Finally, we use the "sharp" module to save the screenshot as a PNG file named "email-screenshot.png".

Note that this code assumes that you have installed the "puppeteer" and "sharp" modules using the "npm" package manager, and that you have set up the appropriate Chromium executable for Puppeteer. You may also need to adjust the selector for the email message area depending on your email client.

If you want to individually control access to each page and control in your ASP.NET MVC Core application, you can define each page and control as a resource and assign it a unique identifier. You can then use these identifiers in your external authorization system, such as Azure AD, to define the access policies for each resource.

Here's an example of how you can define a resource in Azure AD:

1. Define a resource: Define a resource in Azure AD that corresponds to a page or control in your ASP.NET MVC Core application. You can define the resource by adding a new application manifest file in the Azure Portal, and adding a new `resources` property to the manifest. The `resources` property is an array of objects that define each resource.

Here's an example of how you can define a resource in the `resources` property:
```json
"resources": [
