To enable every change of a specified property to be logged, you can create a method in the `Record` class that updates the property value and logs the change in the `Archive` table. For example:
```php
class Record {
    private $table;
    private $values = array();

    public function __construct(Table $table) {
        $this->table = $table;
    }

    public function __get($field_name) {
        if (array_key_exists($field_name, $this->values)) {
            return $this->values[$field_name];
        } else {
            return null;
        }
    }

    public function __set($field_name, $value) {
        $field = $this->table->getField($field_name);
        if ($field != null) {
            $old_value = array_key_exists($field_name, $this->values) ? $this->values[$field_name] : null;
            $this->values[$field_name] = $value;
            $this->table->getDatabase()->getArchive()->addChange($field_name, $old_value, $value);
        }
    }

    public function save() {
        $this->table->addRecord($this);
    }
}
```
In this example, every time the value of a property is updated, the `__set` method logs the change in the `Archive` table by calling the `addChange` method on the `Archive` object.

`Promise.all()`, `Promise.allSettled()`, and `Promise.race()` are all methods that allow you to handle multiple Promises at once. Here's how they differ:

`Promise.all()` takes an array of Promises and returns a new Promise that resolves with an array of values when all of the input Promises have resolved. If any of the input Promises are rejected, the returned Promise is also rejected immediately with the reason of the first rejected Promise.

Example:
```javascript
const promise1 = Promise.resolve(1);
const promise2 = Promise.resolve(2);
const promise3 = Promise.resolve(3);

Promise.all([promise1, promise2, promise3])
  .then(values => console.log(values)); // Output: [1, 2, 3]
```
`Promise.allSettled()` takes an array of Promises and returns a new Promise that resolves with an array of objects when all of the input Promises have settled (i.e., either resolved or rejected). Each object in the returned array has a `status` property indicating whether the Promise was resolved or rejected, and a `value` or `reason` property containing the value or reason of the settled Promise.

Example:
```javascript
const promise1 = Promise.resolve(1);
const promise2 = Promise.reject(new Error("Failed"));
const promise3 = Promise.resolve(3);

Promise.allSettled([promise1, promise2, promise3])
  .then(results => console.log(results)); 
  // Output: [{status: 'fulfilled', value: 1}, {status: 'rejected', reason: Error: Failed}, {status: 'fulfilled', value: 3}]
```
`Promise.race()` takes an array of Promises and returns a new Promise that resolves or rejects as soon as one of the input Promises resolves or rejects. The returned Promise resolves with the value of the first Promise to resolve or rejects with the reason of the first Promise to reject.

Example:
```javascript
const promise1 = new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 1000, "one"));
const promise2 = new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 2000, "two"));

Promise.race([promise1, promise2])
  .then(value => console.log(value)); // Output: "one"
```
In summary, `Promise.all()` resolves when all the input Promises are resolved, `Promise.allSettled()` resolves when all the input Promises have settled, and `Promise.race()` resolves or rejects as soon as one of the input Promises resolves or rejects.

